observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Treasurer agreed to:

1. Intensify its collection efforts for the uncollected stall fees and to henceforth ensure that all rentals are supported by a valid and binding lease contract;

2. Reconcile the variance noted in the monthly rates per master list of stall occupants and the Revenue Code, and indicate the monthly rental rate in the Contract of Lease;

3. Ensure that the granting of Contract of Lease as well as, the levy and collection of taxes and fees is in accordance with the Municipality’s Revenue Code.

We recommended and the MENRO and concerned offices agreed to:

Provide assistance to the barangays in the management of their solid waste and actively promote and enforce the sorting and segregation of wastes at the household level and all other sources;

Ensure that collection of biodegradable/compostable and reusable/recyclable wastes is being done at the barangay level and only non-recyclable materials and special wastes shall be collected pursuant to pertinent provisions of Section 10 of RA No. 9003;

Establish a policy for the generation of revenue from saleable recyclables and include the same in the Municipal Revenue Code; and

Prepare a comprehensive work and financial plan relative to solid waste management operations to establish the timing and extent of implementation of each program, project and activities during the year, and to employ monitoring mechanisms to ensure full implementation thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Officials/ Personnel correct the aforementioned deficiencies and strictly comply to Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2003-003 by adopting the following measures:

Secure from the COA Chairman Credit advice that could serve as evidence for the liquidation of the cash advance of P300,000.00 dated December 21, 2010;

Furnish the Office of the Team Leader, copy of transmittal letter for the purpose, duly received by the COA Chairman or his duly authorized representative.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

The Municipal Accountant see to it that requests for advance payment by contractors are properly supported with the financial instruments required under Section 4, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 before payments are made; 

The Municipal Accountant ensure that the release of retention money meets the conditions stated under Section 6, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;

The Municipal Engineer prepare a Statement of Work Accomplished as of target completion date for projects with delayed completion, and the Municipal Accountant compute the liquidated damages on the basis thereof and withhold the same from payment to contractors in accordance with Section 9, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

The Municipal Engineer and concerned offices, properly determine the ABC of projects pursuant to the guidelines on the computation thereof as provided under General Procurement Manual Volume III; and

The Municipal Accountant properly account and record the advance payments, progress payments, and withholding of retention money on disbursements for infrastructure projects pursuant to applicable accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended and Management has agreed that:

The HRMO ensure that all outsourced workers are covered with a binding contract and/or other appropriate documents;

The HRMO and concerned offices formulate policies/guidelines in engaging and managing outsourced workers and in the granting of wages and allowances;

The HRMO specify in the contracts the office assignment, fund source, and whether the personnel is allowed to report to work during weekends, and ensure that all accomplishments reported are quantifiable to allow verification with the stated duties and functions per Contracts; and 

The HRMO and Municipal Accountant make certain that validation is made as to the number of days worked per payroll and DTR, with the stated working days as agreed upon in the Contracts, and all claims are supported with documents that are complete and proper before payment is made.

We recommended that the LCE direct the following:
Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory count of all properties and take on the responsibilities as prescribed under Section 156 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Municipal Accountant and GSO to update the PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, for proper identification of all PPE;
Personnel responsible to prepare the RPCPPE and reconcile the balances between the Accounting and General Services Office; and
Creation of an Appraisal Committee to assist in the disposal of unserviceable properties; the person responsible to submit the IIRUP to the COA Office as required in the guidelines; and thereafter, the Accounting Office to record journal entries for the dropping of PPEs from the books of accounts once the unserviceable properties were properly disposed.

We recommended that the LCE direct the concerned officials and employees to take immediate actions on the matters listed below:
Maintain and update a GAD Database that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
Ensure submission of the annual status reports on the Institutional Mechanisms for Gender Mainstreamingand GAD AR in required format to the DILG Regional Office and to the Office of the Auditor;
Ensure the full utilization of the allocated budget and propose plans/ programs for GAD, PWDs and the Youth to maximize the funds and benefits thereof and ensure that the relevant LGU PPAs and GAD activities will address/respond to the gender issues identified; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned officials and employees to take immediate actions on the matters listed below:
Ensure that their GFPS is fully-functional and the members have the capacity and influence to promote gender mainstreaming pursuant to Section 37 of the MCW IRR;
Set-up and maintain a GAD Database that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; Also, formulate GAD Codes or Ordinances that will support the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights, economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment;
Ensure submission of the Annual GPB and GAD Accomplishment Report in required format to the DILG RO VI for review and approval to ascertain compliance with the guidelines;
Ensure the full utilization of the allocated budget and propose plans/ programs for GAD, PWDs and the Youth to maximize the funds and benefits thereof and ensure that the relevant LGU PPAs and GAD activities of the Municipality will address/respond to the gender issues identified; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

We recommended that the LCE direct the concerned officials and employees to take immediate actions on the following matters:
Ensure that their GFPS is fully-functional and the members have the capacity and influence to promote gender mainstreaming pursuant to Section 37 of the MCW Implementing Rules and Regulations (MCW IRR);
Set-up and maintain a GAD Database that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; Also, formulate GAD Codes or Ordinances that will support the Municipality’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights, economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment;
Ensure submission of the Annual GPB and GAD AR in required format to the DILG Regional Office VI for review and approval to ascertain compliance with the guidelines;
Ensure the full utilization of the allocated budget and propose plans/ programs for GAD, PWDs and the Youth to maximize the funds and benefits thereof and ensure that the relevant PPAs and GAD activities will address/respond to the gender issues identified; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

We recommended that:
The LCE designate a Focal Person for the SWM Office for the implementation of the program;
The LCE directly instruct the concerned employees to create a SWM Plan in adherence to RA No. 9003;
The Municipality create a SWM Board and prioritize the preparation of the 10-Year SWM Plan and have it approved by the National SWM Commission  to ensure that the required efficient solid waste management is met;
The Municipality require the strict implementation of waste segregation at source through coordination with the Barangay Officials  on the campaign of proper segregation and disposal of wastes; and
The Officer-in-Charge on the collection of wastes be equipped with proper personal protective gear and observe the use of separate compartment/container with cover for specific types of wastes to ensure the containment of solid wastes while in transit.

We recommended that the LCE, as the Chairman, and other members of the GFPS, undertake GAD planning in accordance with the provisions of PCW/ DILG/ DBM/NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, to ensure that appropriate gender issues are identified and are the existing concerns/problems in the municipality, and see to it that the relevant LGU PPAs and GAD activities will address/respond to such gender issues identified.
We also recommended that the GFPS observe the proper implementation of the PPAs and optimize the utilization of the GAD budget as planned to meet/attain the objectives of GAD set by the government.
Further, we recommended the following:
Set-up and maintain a GAD Database that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
Prepare the GAD AR in accordance with the procedures and format provided in the JMC No. 2013-01 and support it with the necessary documents;
Ensure submission of the Annual GPB and GAD AR to the DILG Regional Office VI for review and approval to ascertain compliance with the guidelines.

We recommended that the LCE direct the concerned officials and employees in-charge/assigned in the implementation of the SWM Program in the Municipality to adhere strictly to the provisions of RA No. 9003.
We also recommended the following:
Require the strict implementation of  waste segregation at source;
Implement the separate collection schedules for specific types of wastes, and ensure that such shall cover all the barangays in the Municipality;
Observe the use of separate compartment/container with cover  for specific types of wastes  to ensure the containment of solid wastes while in transit;
Coordinate with Barangay Officials regarding information dissemination/ campaign on proper segregation and disposal of wastes to be implemented in the barangay;
Create a SWM Board and prioritize the preparation of the 10-Year SWM Plan and have it approved by the National Solid Waste Management Commission to ensure that the required efficient solid waste management is met;
Make representations with the Sangguniang Bayan for the establishment/ creation of an Ordinance providing for the management of solid waste in the Municipality.
